        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">Fire Extinguisher Inspection in Gilbert, AZ: What Every Business Owner Needs to Know</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-500 leading-relaxed mb-8">If you own or manage a commercial property in Gilbert, AZ, your fire extinguishers are a legal requirement with specific inspection schedules enforced by the Gilbert Fire and Rescue. Here's exactly what NFPA 10 and the Arizona Fire Code (IFC-based) require, what inspections cost, and how to avoid violations.</p>
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-3">Gilbert Fire Extinguisher Requirements</h2>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">The City of Gilbert enforces the Arizona Fire Code (IFC-based), requiring all commercial properties to maintain portable fire extinguishers in compliance with <a href="/compliance/nfpa-10/" class="text-red-brand hover:underline">NFPA 10: Standard for Portable Fire Extinguishers</a>. Gilbert has grown from a small agricultural town into one of the Phoenix metro's fastest-growing commercial communities. The Heritage District's restaurant and entertainment corridor, Santan Village retail and restaurant complex, and growing corporate campus and medical office development along the Loop 202 all require fire extinguisher compliance. Gilbert Fire and Rescue is one of the most active fire prevention divisions in Maricopa County for new commercial construction and existing building compliance.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Monthly Visual Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Monthly visual inspections can be performed by trained building staff — no license required. Verify each extinguisher is in its designated location, unobstructed, the pressure gauge reads in the operating range, and the tamper seal and pull pin are intact. Document every check. Absence of monthly records significantly increases liability exposure in the event of an incident or enforcement action.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">Annual Professional Inspections</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Annual inspections must be performed by a licensed technician who inspects mechanical parts, agent condition, pressure gauge, hose and nozzle, and attaches a dated service tag. Arizona requires fire extinguisher service contractors to hold appropriate credentials under Arizona state law, overseen by the Arizona State Fire Marshal's Office (602-364-1003). Verify your service provider holds current Arizona credentials before scheduling service. Any failed unit must be immediately serviced, recharged, or replaced.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">6-Year Internal Examination</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">Every six years, stored-pressure extinguishers must be emptied, disassembled, and internally examined for corrosion and agent degradation. This typically includes a full recharge after examination. Missing the 6-year exam is frequently cited during Gilbert Fire and Rescue commercial property inspections.</p>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mb-3">12-Year Hydrostatic Testing</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">At 12 years, extinguisher cylinders must pass hydrostatic pressure testing to verify structural integrity. Units that fail must be condemned and cannot be returned to service. Budget for some units to require replacement at this interval.</p>
